The paper deals with matroids, which are a fundamental concept in discrete mathematics and algorithms. The paper presents a fast computation of representative families for uniform matroids, which has applications in solving various algorithmic problems. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also involves computational geometry, as it deals with subsets of a set, and thus could be categorized under cs.CG (Computational Geometry). The paper also involves combinatorics, as it deals with families of subsets, and thus could be categorized under cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The paper also involves complexity theory, as it presents improved running times for various algorithmic problems, and thus could be categorized under cs.CC (Computational Complexity). Finally, the paper also involves game theory, as it deals with out-branching, and thus could be categorized under cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory).
